    lng: 8.4689,
    summary: `Norway is the country that solved the "resource curse"—it struck oil in the North Sea and instead of blowing the wealth on corruption and palaces, built the world's largest sovereign wealth fund ($1.6+ trillion) and became a model of Scandinavian social democracy. The result: a nation with near-zero poverty, excellent infrastructure, gender equality, environmental consciousness, and landscapes so stunning they make you understand why Vikings worshipped nature gods. Fjords, northern lights, midnight sun, Viking heritage, modern design, and a quality of life consistently ranked among the world's highest. The catch: Norway is eye-wateringly expensive. A beer costs $12, a hostel bed $50, a pizza $25. But if you can afford it—or budget carefully—Norway delivers one of the great travel experiences. This is a country where you can kayak in a fjord at midnight under the Arctic sun, hike to a glacier, eat reindeer in a 900-year-old stave church town, and take a train ride (Bergen Railway, Flåm Railway) that belongs on a bucket list. Just bring your credit card and a tolerance for $30 sandwiches.

**Must-See Destinations**: The fjords are Norway's signature. Geirangerfjord and Nærøyfjord (both UNESCO sites) are the classics—steep cliffs, waterfalls, deep blue water, accessible by ferry, cruise, or kayak. Bergen, the gateway city, has Bryggen (colorful Hanseatic wharf, UNESCO site), the fish market, funicular to Mount Fløyen for views, and access to the fjord region. The Flåm Railway from Flåm to Myrdal is one of the world's most scenic train rides—20km, 860m elevation gain, waterfalls and valleys. The Bergen Railway from Bergen to Oslo crosses the Hardangervidda plateau—stunning high-altitude scenery. The Lofoten Islands in the Arctic are Norway's postcard: jagged peaks rising from the sea, fishing villages like Reine and Henningsvær, midnight sun (May-July), northern lights (September-March), hiking, and cod-drying racks. Tromsø, the "Gateway to the Arctic," is northern lights central, dog sledding, whale watching, and the Arctic Cathedral. Oslo has Viking Ship Museum, Vigeland Sculpture Park, the Opera House, Munch Museum (The Scream), and a vibrant food scene.

**Hidden Gems**: The Atlantic Road near Molde—a 8.3km road across islands and bridges over the ocean, dramatic and photogenic. The Vega Archipelago (UNESCO site) off the mid-coast has eider ducks, isolated islands, and traditional culture. Røros, an inland mining town, is a UNESCO site with colorful wooden buildings and Sami influence. Jotunheimen National Park has Norway's highest peaks (Galdhøpiggen, 2,469m) and excellent multi-day hiking. Svalbard, the Arctic archipelago 1,000km north of mainland Norway, is polar bear territory—glaciers, coal-mining history, northernmost settlement in the world (Longyearbyen), accessible by flight from Tromsø (expensive but unique). The Trolltunga hike (10-12 hours round trip) is challenging but rewards with a rock ledge jutting over a lake—Instagram famous. Preikestolen (Pulpit Rock) and Kjeragbolten are other dramatic cliff hikes. The Sami culture in the north (Kautokeino, Karasjok) offers reindeer herding, traditional crafts, and perspectives on indigenous life.

**Infrastructure**: Norway has world-class infrastructure. Oslo's Gardermoen Airport is a major hub; regional airports connect smaller cities. Trains (NSB, now Vy) are excellent—clean, punctual, scenic. The Bergen Railway, Dovre Railway, and Nordland Railway are experiences in themselves. Buses (Nor-Way Bussekspress) reach where trains don't. Ferries are essential in the fjords—Hurtigruten coastal express runs the entire coast Bergen to Kirkenes, part transport, part cruise. Renting a car is expensive ($70-100+/day) but gives flexibility; roads are excellent, tunnels and bridges are engineering marvels. EV charging is ubiquitous (Norway leads the world in EV adoption). Accommodations: hostels ($50-80/night), hotels ($150-250+), cabins (hytte) are a cultural experience ($100-200). Wild camping is legal (allemannsretten—right to roam) if you're 150m from buildings. English is nearly universal. Public transport in Oslo is efficient; smaller towns walkable.

**Safety & Security**: Norway is extremely safe—among the world's lowest crime rates. Violent crime is rare; petty theft in Oslo happens occasionally. Police are professional and helpful. The real risks are environmental: weather in the mountains can change rapidly—hikers die from hypothermia, avalanches (winter/spring), and underestimating terrain. Proper gear and planning are essential. Polar bears in Svalbard are a real danger—don't leave settlements without a rifle or guide. Roads in winter require winter tires and driving skills; summer tourists underestimate distances. Darkness in winter (polar night above Arctic Circle) and constant daylight in summer (midnight sun) can be disorienting.

**Visa Requirements**: Norway is in the Schengen Area. US, Canada, UK, Australia, New Zealand, and many others get 90 days visa-free (in any 180-day period). ETIAS authorization (€7, online, valid 3 years) is required starting late 2024 for visa-exempt nationals. Non-Schengen nationals may need visas. No vaccinations required. Norway is not in the EU, but Schengen rules apply.

**Best Times to Visit**: May-September is peak season—midnight sun in the north (late May-July), warmest temps (15-25°C in south, cooler in north), hiking season, long days, but maximum prices and crowds. June-August is ideal for fjords and Lofoten. September is shoulder season: fall colors, northern lights start, fewer tourists, lower prices, but cooler. October-April is winter: skiing, northern lights (best November-March), but very cold (-5 to -30°C in the north), short daylight (polar night in far north December-January). February-March is ski season. April is transitional—melting snow, cheaper, but weather unpredictable. Late May and September are sweet spots.

**Tourist Numbers**: Norway welcomed about 6-7 million international visitors in 2023, recovering toward pre-pandemic levels. Germans, Swedes, Danes, Brits, and Americans dominate. Tourism is 4-5% of GDP—important but not dominant (oil and gas dwarf it). Over-tourism is an issue at iconic spots: Trolltunga, Preikestolen, Geirangerfjord in summer see crowds, parking chaos, and environmental strain. The government is managing via permits, shuttles, and fees. Rural Norway sees few tourists.

**The Bottom Line**: Norway is jaw-droppingly beautiful and punishingly expensive. If you can handle the costs (budget $100-150/day minimum for basics, $200-300+ for comfort), it's one of the world's great destinations. The fjords, mountains, and Arctic landscapes are sublime. The infrastructure makes travel easy and comfortable. The culture is low-key, egalitarian, and design-forward. The cities (Oslo, Bergen, Tromsø) are clean, safe, and culturally rich. And the Norwegians, while reserved, are helpful and almost universally speak perfect English. The challenges: prices will shock you ($40 for a pizza, $100 for a mediocre hotel), weather is unpredictable (pack layers), and summer crowds at famous spots can feel like Disneyland. But Norway rewards planning: camp or stay in hytteer, cook your own food, visit shoulder seasons, explore lesser-known regions (the west coast north of Bergen, inland Jotunheimen, the far north beyond Tromsø). The Scandinavian model works—low inequality, high trust, environmental stewardship—and you see it in the quality of everything. Norway is expensive because it values labor, sustainability, and quality of life over maximizing profit. As a tourist, you pay for that. And honestly, it's worth it.`
